{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01QmTm1jhYdtvFpWcwYj3v6A","type":"tool_result","content":"File created successfully at: /Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/input/Elderberry Fool.generated.21.txt"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"926db9e7-9037-44e8-846b-5b4fe7c8d30b","uuid":"14d5126b-ce1d-482c-9228-472ce5f317e2","tool_use_result":{"type":"create","filePath":"/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/input/Elderberry Fool.generated.21.txt","content":"page 287 | TRADITIONAL DESSERTS\n\nElderberry Fool\n\n[Technique: Whipped Cream Fold]\n\nPreparation time: 15 minutes | Chilling: 1 hour\n\nIngredients needed:\n\n1 lb fresh elderberries (or frozen, thawed)\n¼ cup sugar\n2 tbsp elderflower cordial or water\n1 cup heavy cream\n2 tbsp powdered sugar\n1 tsp vanilla extract\nPinch of salt\nFresh mint for garnish\n\nRecipe:\n\nCook elderberries with sugar and elderflower cordial\nin a saucepan over low heat for 8-10 minutes until\nberries are very soft and slightly broken down.\nPass through fine sieve or food mill to remove seeds.\nCool completely to room temperature.\nIn separate bowl, whip heavy cream with powdered sugar,\nvanilla, and salt until stiff peaks form.\nGently fold cooled elderberry compote into whipped cream\nin two additions, creating marbled effect.\nDivide into serving glasses.\nChill for at least 1 hour before serving.\nTop with fresh mint leaf.\n\nServes: 4-6\n\nNotes: This dessert should be served well chilled. If\nusing frozen berries, thaw completely and drain excess\nliquid before cooking. May be made up to 4 hours ahead.\n","structuredPatch":[],"originalFile":null}}
